               <head>Risalah dar hay'at</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Risālah dar hay’at</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85009003" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Or_15759-item1">
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_4319">Risālah dar hay’at</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_4319">رساله در هيئة</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>An untitled treatise on the basics of astronomy and geometry comprising a muqaddimah, two maqālahs, and (unannounced in the author’s preface) a khātimah. </p>
                        <p>This work is not identifiable as one in published catalogues. Its plan and incipit, however, resemble those of the treatise by <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="viaf_90047204" ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/nr90029107" role="aut">‘Alā’ al-Dīn ‘Alī ibn Muḥammad Qūshchī</persName> (d. 879/1474) generally known as <title>Risālah-’i hay’at</title>, from which it may in part be derived. 
                        </p>
                        <p>Contents: Maqālah 1 (f. 6v-33v): Dar bayān-i ajrām-i ‘ulvī; on the heavenly bodies. Maqālah 2 (33v-59r): Dar bayān-i hay’at-i zamīn va qismat-i ū bi-aqālīm; on the composition of the Earth, and its division into climes. Khātimah (57v-59r): Dar ma‘rifat-i ab‘ād va ajrām; on determining dimensions and mass. </p>
                        <p>Other contents: f. 1r, apparently a brief exercise in naskhī calligraphy; 1v, verses in praise of ‘Alī, in shikastah, and an Arabic prayer for healing, both introduced in Persian; 3r, verses by <addName/>
                           <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="viaf_50413291" ref="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n90674546" role="aut">ʻUrfī</persName> (b. 963/1555-6) and others, including a mnemonic poem on the zodiac sign names of the months, a definition in Arabic of al-falak al-a‘ẓam, and a note dated 1237/1821; 32v, a doodle; 59r, description of the astrolabe; 59v, quotations from works on geometry, lines of verses blessing the Prophet, and others concerning Ibn Sīnā; 60r, an extract from a treatise concerning astrolabes; 60v, ruba'is attributed to the Sufi master <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="viaf_5721767" ref="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n88155215" role="aut">Abū Sa‘īd ibn Abī l-Khayr</persName> (d. 440/1049), and other verses in Arabic. 
                        </p>
                        <p>The present manuscript contains copious marginal notes, most of which are in Arabic, throughout. </p>
                        <p>Ownership seals on f. 3r, 28r, 54v, 59r. </p>
                        <p>Title supplied. </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="per" otherLangs="ara">Persian with marginal notes mostly in Arabic</textLang>
